SIMPLE: frazzle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frazzle
<hw>Fraz"zle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Frazzled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Frazzling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. G.
<ets>faseln</ets>, and E. <ets>fray</ets>.]</ety> <def>To fray; to wear
or pull into tatters or tag ends; to tatter; -- used literally and
figuratively.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her hair was of a reddish gray color, and its <qex>frazzled</qex>
and tangled condition suggested that the woman had recently passed
through a period of extreme excitement.</q> <rj><qau>J. C.
Harris.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frazzle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frazzle
<hw>Fraz"zle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or result of
frazzling; the condition or quality of being frazzled; the tag end; a
frayed-out end.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng. & U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>My fingers are all scratched to <qex>frazzles</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Kipling.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a state of extreme exhaustion; -- often used in the
phrase <col><b>worn to a frazzle</b></col>.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gordon had sent word to Lee that he ⟦ldquo⟧had fought his corps to
a <qex>frazzle</qex>.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Nicolay & Hay (Life of
Lincoln).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Freak</ent>⟦br⟧
